  "dateModified": "2026-03-05",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-05",
  "description": "Meter is the abstract pattern that a metrical poem keeps a near-bargain with — a fixed template of stressed and unstressed syllables, of syllable counts, or of long and short syllables, against which each spoken line is heard. The word comes from Greek métron (\u0026ldquo;measure\u0026rdquo;), and the measuring is the point: a metrical line is one whose ear-shape has been counted in advance.\nMeter does not live on the page. It lives in the listener. A line of iambic pentameter does not become metrical because a poet has typed ten syllables; it becomes metrical because a reader who knows the pattern hears each syllable land on or off the beat the pattern predicts. The poem and the reader together perform the meter — the poem proposes it, the reader carries it, and the spoken line either fulfills, delays, or breaks it. This is why meter has expressive force. A line that meets the pattern exactly settles into it; a line that violates the pattern registers as violation only because the pattern is already in the ear.\n",
  "name": "Meter",
